sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1041000
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Mutagenesis was used to add a Nde1 site at the start of the RFP coding region of the biobrick BBa_J04450. This enables a restriction digest with Nde1 to be performed allowing the RFP coding region to be excised from the plasmid.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: NRP UEA
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Nde1 site was added at the start of the RFP coding region.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1321300
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: pSEVA331-Bb - pSEVA331 with biobrick prefix and suffix
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is pSEVA331 converted into a biobrick compatible format by substituting the original multiple cloning site for biobrick prefix and suffix. pSEVA331 is a broad host range plasmid, capable of replication in E.coli and several other organisms. It is capable of replication in the cellulose producing bacterium Gluconacetobacter xylinum. We have used it as our standard backbone for G.xylinum genetic engineering.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Michael Florea
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The original pSEVA331 backbone comes from the SEVA (Standard European Vector Architecture) collection.
